## 5. SHIP-SAFE OPERATIONS & GROWTH (Sources 7–11, Jun 2026)

### 5.1 Test your own security before attackers do (Source 7)
> "You built all the right security features… but have you ever tried to hack your own app?"
- [ ] Run **OWASP ZAP** against staging — crawls the app, tests the OWASP Top 10
      (SQLi, XSS, broken auth). One Docker command, free.
- [ ] **Burp Suite** your own API: intercept a request and tamper with it —
      change the user ID in the JWT, swap `org_id` in the body, modify the `role`
      claim. If you can read another tenant's data or hit admin endpoints, your
      authorization has holes. **RLS alone is not enough** if the API passes
      unchecked params to the DB.
- [ ] **Automate security scanning in CI** (we do): Trivy (deps/CVEs) + Gitleaks
      (secrets) + **CodeQL** (static analysis) on every push/PR. See `.github/workflows/ci.yml`.

### 5.2 AI reviews the code your AI wrote (Source 8)
> "The AI wrote your code. You shipped it without reading it. Now you have tech debt you don't understand."
- [ ] Add an **AI reviewer to the PR pipeline** (we have **Bugbot**; CodeRabbit/
      custom Claude action are alternatives). Every PR gets an automated review.
- [ ] **Prompt for architecture, not syntax**: business-logic correctness, SQLi
      vectors, unhandled edge cases, N+1 queries, anything touching payments or
      data deletion. Tell it to ignore style nits.
- [ ] **Gate merges**: critical findings block; warnings inform. You are the
      orchestrator making the final call.

### 5.3 Survive your first 100 users (Source 9)
> "50 people sign up, the database locks up, blank screen of death."
- [ ] **Connection pooling** on the DB (PgBouncer / Supabase pooler). Don't open a
      new connection per request.
- [ ] **Caching layer** (Redis / Upstash / in-memory) for data that doesn't change
      every second — cuts response time and DB load dramatically.
- [ ] **Load test before launch** with **k6** or **artillery** (free, ~30 min):
      simulate 100 concurrent users, find the bottleneck before users do.
      (We have `tests/performance/`.)
- [ ] Scale beyond 1k→10k users (Source 13): **async job queues** (Celery/Redis —
      we have this) so heavy work (email, transcription, doc scanning) never locks
      the request; **targeted DB indexes**; and when one box isn't enough,
      **horizontal scaling** (multiple backend instances behind a load balancer).

### 5.5 Pass Apple's ~90-second human review (Source 12)
> "Apple has a human reviewing your app for ninety seconds. Here's how to not get rejected."
- [ ] **Working demo credentials in App Review notes** (we use `demo-screenshots@palmtai.com`).
      No login = instant rejection. No placeholder/"lorem" content visible.
- [ ] **Justify every permission** (camera, mic, location) in the usage strings.
      Unjustified prompts get rejected.
- [ ] **Disclose AI-generated content** where the app produces it.
- [ ] **Screenshots must match the live app** — don't show features that aren't built.
- [ ] **Digital goods → Apple IAP**; remove any external "buy" path from the app.
- [ ] **Sign in with Apple is required** if you offer any third-party social login
      (Google/Facebook, etc.). ⚠️ Verify in `ios-app`.
- [ ] **In-app account deletion is required** if users can create accounts. ⚠️ Verify
      there's a delete-account flow inside the app, not just a web/email request.

### 5.4 SEO + AEO = helpful content, not gimmicks (Sources 10 & 11)
> Google's 2026 AEO/GEO guide: AI Overviews use the **same quality signals as normal SEO**.
- [ ] **Don't** over-engineer AI-only schema or depend on `llms.txt` for Google —
      Google extracts relevant passages itself and can **penalize** attempts to
      game generative responses. (`llms.txt` still helps non-Google engines; keep it lean.)
- [ ] **Do** write genuinely helpful, question-targeted content. Mine real
      questions (e.g. AnswerThePublic), answer them with your real expertise,
      experience, case studies, and opinions. Two quality posts a week beats tricks.
- [ ] Keep SEO fundamentals solid: unique titles/descriptions, one H1, clean URLs,
      canonical tags, sitemap derived from real content, FAQ/Article/Breadcrumb
      structured data, fast Core Web Vitals.
- [ ] Fill SaaS content gaps: **pricing**, **comparison/alternative**, and
      **how-to** pages (these win high-intent search). See `apps/web/src/app/blog/`.
- [ ] **AEO extractability** (`ai-seo` skill): lead each section with a 40–60 word
      answer; add a "What is X?" definition block; use **comparison tables**
      (≈33% of AI citations); cite real stats with sources (never fabricated).
- [ ] **Machine-readable files** for AI engines + buying agents: `llms.txt` and
      `/pricing.md` (structured, real numbers). Keep pricing public, not behind
      "contact sales" or JS-only walls.
- [ ] **Don't block AI crawlers** you want citations from (GPTBot, PerplexityBot,
      ClaudeBot, Google-Extended). Block training-only bots (CCBot) only if needed.
- [ ] Keep structured data accurate (Offer prices must match the real pricing page).

